<br>
Please note...  I do not hate Christians.  However, I do object strenuously to any attempt to make ME or anyone else become one unwillingly.  Schools should not be preaching religion, if anything they should be teaching about all the different religions but I don't see that happening any time soon.<br>
<br>
sorry for the soapbox...  I feel real strongly about this issue though.<br>
<br>
Taerianaya <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uhiraghm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hiraghm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Dubious Poster</span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#778899>(10/23/01 7:55:28 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.com/jdwilliams2/data/Aldrinshroom1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pledge of Allegiance</span><hr size=1> When &quot;under God&quot; was added is no big deal, so long as it was added by Congress. I have a problem with ordinary people changing things like that for just their agenda du jour, too. I don't have a problem with people pledging allegiance to the nation, though like with most such things it often becomes more ceremony than meaningful (like feeling someone's pain rather than doing something to alleviate it...) but I do feel nervous about a set, rote phrase to be used. As agnostic, the under God part doesn't bother me; after all, jews, christians and moslems all believe in the same God, just different interpretations of him, and they make up the vast vast majority of people in the country. If you happen to be a wiccan, you can say something stupid instead, like &quot;Earth Mother&quot; or whatever (sorry, I have contempt for wiccans, druids and other tree huggers <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) If you're satanists, you can get to a psychiatrist. If you are a pantheist, pick your favorite or change God to &quot;the gods&quot;. If you're Amish, or one of the religions that forbid such pledges, don't take the pledge.<br>
While it may make kids feel uncomfortable and left-out to not join in a pledge their parents disapprove of, it is standing up for one's beliefs in such adverse circumstances that builds character, in my opinion. After all, what character does it take to stand up for a principle that everyone agrees with?<br>
I have a related problem,  in regard to your comment about the resurgence of patriotism. And that's people thinking they're being patriotic by have a flag plastered somewhere, like a happy face. I truly grow annoyed when I see some bugger wearing a flag on his t-shirt, or wearing a flag bandanna. If you care enough to go to the lazy arsed trouble of plunking 10 bucks down for a shirt or bandanna, go to the trouble of learning the *rules* regarding the display of the flag, one of which is that it's not to be worn as an article of clothing. I see people hanging the flag upside down or backwards, and for years I have griped at car dealerships and other places displaying huge, tattered flags. &quot;Well, they're expensive to replace!&quot; Hey, then don't fly them! Nobody says you have to! I once had to stop at a fire station to get them to change their tattered flag. The explanation was that the new one hadn't come in yet; the next day, a new one was flying. I know I'm an *$$h0le about this, but it's consistent with my belief that actions speak louder than words.<br>
<br>
Aldrin Moonwalker(dammit, my soapbox is wearing out...)<br>
