<br>
No one ever mentioned how, not 30 minutes before, the entire school stood up at the same time to recite The Pledge.<br>
<br>
Requiring children to recite the Pledge is Hoo-Rah Propaganda. <br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong. I'm a patriot. I even served in the Armed Forces. I've never missed voting in any primary or general election I have ever been eligible to vote in. I pay my taxes, I take pains to stay informed and when I vote, I think about what's good for my city/county/state/country/world, and not just what's going to give me the most benefit. <br>
<br>
However, I want my children to have learned the history of our country, and the histories of other countries, and to appreciate the liberties, freedoms, and (most of all) responsibilities we have as Americans, so that they can recite the Pledge and mean it (if that is their choice), rather than to hear them recite it because that's what the teacher told them to do. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uhiraghm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hiraghm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Indifferent Poster</span><br>  Posts: 204<br> <font color=#778899>(10/24/01 4:33:39 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.com/jdwilliams2/data/Aldrinshroom1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pledge of Allegiance</span><hr size=1> &quot;How can the attitude of 200 million people be switched on and off like a light bulb? How can one set of facts be made to produce three widely differing pravdas? By complete control of all communications from cradel to the grave.<br>
&quot;Almost all Soviet women work. Their babies are place in kindergartens at an average age of 57 days, so we were told, and what we saw supported the allegation. We visisted several kindergartens, on collective farms and in factories. By the posted schedules these babies spend 13 1/2 hours each day in kindergarten - they are with their mothers for perhaps an hour before bedtime.<br>
&quot;At the Forty-Years_of_October Collective Farm outside Alma Ata some of the older children in one of the kindergartens put on a little show for us. One little girl recited a poem. A little boy gave a prose recitation. The entire group sang. The cildren were clean and neat, healthy and happy. Our guide translated nothing, so superficially, it wa the sort of beguiling performance one sees any day in any American kindergarten.<br>
&quot;However, my wife understands Russian:<br>
  The poem recounted the life of Lenin.<br>
  The prose recitation concerned the Seven-year Plan.<br>
  The group singing was about how &quot;we must protect our Revolution.&quot;<br>
&quot;These tots were no older than six.<br>
&quot;That is how it is done. Starting at the cradle, never let them haer anything but the official version. Thus 'pravda' becomes 'truth' to the Russian Children.&quot; - Robert A. Heinlein &quot;Pravda Means 'Truth'&quot;, an account of his visit to the Soviet Union in the early 1960s. <br>
He goes on to explain the results of such indoctrination; an intourist guide becomes angry and abusive when Heinlein's wife informs a fellow foreigner that Vilno is the capital of Lithuania, one of the formerly independent Baltic republics. According to this guide, Lithuania was *always* a part of the Soviet Union.<br>
<br>
How does this apply to U.S.? I'm not concerned with children reciting a pledge of loyalty to their native country. I'm concerned with children being inundated day and night by propoganda from the tv portraying men as abusive and weak; propoganda suggesting that all bad things prior to 1960 were due to anglo male insecurity, and all things wonderful and good were due to wise, kind liberals who even then (even though anglo and male) knew that things should be as they are today. I'm more concerned with children who have so little knowledge of history that the idea of not offending the perpetrators of Pearl Harbor during last December's commemoration sounds rational to them. I'm more concerned with jr high school children claiming to feel nothing for their nation, and their own principal concuring this sentiment. I'm more concerned with female idiot teachers (now there's a redundancy for you...) suggesting that algebra I and II not be required *high school* subjects, because it might discourage the little darlings. Let them take business math instead (my mother pointed out to me that when she was in school, she didn't have a choice.. she took *both*.) I'm more concerned with an entire society where it is forbidden to offend specific classes of citizens, but not only allowed, but *encouraged* to insult and offend certain other classes. I'm concerned about a society where a teacher can remove a picture posted on a boy's locker portraying the persecution of enemies of his nation (a picture of planes bombing Afghanistan with United and American Airline logos on them,) and merely be taken to court to get the boy's supsension lifted (instead of losing his job.) I'm far more concerned about propoganda which frequently portrays females physically abusing males and being rewarded and applauded for it. I'm far more concerned about children being indoctrinated in &quot;global warming&quot; hysteria, of being constantly inundated with tales of how terrible their species is, how their ONE TOOL for making the world better, technology, is the cause of all problems. I'm more concerned about children being raised by strangers in day-care centers or baby-sitters who are little more than children themselves so mommy and daddy can pursue &quot;careers&quot;; meanwhile the children learning the common mindless propoganda of the lowest common denominator at the hands of those strangers, whose own kids are quite likely in another day-care facility.<br>
I'm excessively concerned that children are being taught that there's nothing, nobody, no idea that they can cling to as an absolute. No dad *and* mom there, always. No oath truly binding &quot;til death do us part&quot;, no absolutes of good and evil, of moral and immoral. I worry about propoganda spewing forth from the networks and hollywood and even the gov't itself, suggesting that there's no difference between your loved ones and strangers; no difference between men who &quot;shoot their prisoners, enslave their citizens, and deride the dignity of man&quot; and those &quot;to whom the individual and his indiviual rights are sacred&quot; (in the words of General Matt Ridgeway.) I'm terrified of a propoganda machine that insists on portraying the alleged abuses by the europeans who created civilization on the N. American continent of then-native populations as being emotional in intent and entirely one-sided, refuses to point out that mankind is better on the whole (including the decendants of the alleged victims) for it, and blithely ignores the similar abuses taking place between various factions long before Europeans set foot on the continent. I'm far more deeply concerned about public mores being so twisted in a 30-year propoganda campaign that at the end of it the coupling of sexual deviants is equated with the lifetime commitment of man and wife, the society's children not knowing the difference, and anyone suggesting otherwise being hatefully and desperately demonized as fearful and ignorant. I'm disgusted, yet no less concerned with a media and educational indoctrination of the young that focusses on the exception represented by abusiveness and deceit rather than the charitable and honest reality of pre-revolutionary society. <br>
No, I refuse to take the pledge, as an adult, because I believe the very words contradict the truths stated in the Declaration of Independence. &quot;one nation, indivisible&quot; cannot exist so long as men reserve the right to &quot;dissolve those ties which have bound them to another.&quot; (taken from memory, therefore not word-for-word aligned with the DoI.)<br>
But there's nothing wrong with a child being taught that a nation dedicated to the precepts of individual liberty and self-determination is worthy of their allegiance. There's nothing wrong with a child being made to realise that, by and large, the people of his nation believe that they, as a nation, are answerable to a higher, benign and caring power. I was taught this, and remain agnostic. There's nothing wrong in making them aware that their nation is, unlike most, a republic, not a democracy. Unfortunately, there is no way, in the span of a short pledge, of showing those same children that the flag to which they are pledging allegiance is being defended by young men just like what half of them will grow up to be, that such people are superior because of the values embraced by their nation; no way of demonstrating with words in that pledge that there are men (and even women) who in the words of an old song, &quot;mean just what they say.&quot; No way a pledge can describe men, with their dying breath holding that colored piece of cloth aloft hoping to keep it from touching the ground before another can raise it again. No way to make them understand the frustration of men piling cartons of icecream around the flagstaff to keep that bit of material from burning as their ship sinks beneath them and MITSUBISHIs strafe and bomb their decks, simply because there was nothing else they could do. No, the pledge, by itself, is just so many words, prattled mindlessly. Unless those reciting it can, by other means, be made aware of what that silly looking bit of red and white striped material has meant to people of character, people worthy of emulation, people of faith, and dignity and honesty, and be made equally aware that moral relativism is no substitute for the most insigificant feeling of loyalty or integrity.<br>
I began by quoting Heinlein, I'll end by quoting him:<br>
&quot;But there is no way of forcing patriotism on anyone. Passing a law will not create it, nor can we buy it by appropriating so many billions of dollars.&quot; - R.A.H. 'The Pragmatics of Patriotism'<br>
We can't force it, but we can teach it. And if the children are simply made to know the truth about themselves, their species, and their nation, they won't have to be told to recite the pledge; it will engrave itself upon their hearts, upon their souls for the rest of their lives.<br>
<br>
